<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHERIFF'S MOORPARK DIVISION GETS NEW LEADER; PERSONNEL: LT. MARTIN ROUSE, 37, A 
16-YEAR VETERAN OF THE DEPARTMENT, WILL REPLACE LT. GEOFF DEAN IN HEADING THE 
20-MEMBER TEAM. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A lieutenant for the Ventura County Sheriff's Department, promoted just a 
month ago from sergeant, was named Thursday to take control of the department's 
20-member Moorpark division. 
</P>
<P>
 Lt. Martin Rouse, 37, will take over from Lt. Geoff Dean, who has headed the 
Moorpark law enforcement team since August, 1991. Dean is moving to a new 
assignment as an administrator at the new county jail on Todd Road near Santa 
Paula. 
</P>
<P>
 Rouse, a 16-year veteran of the Sheriff's Department, has worked in Moorpark 
for more than four years. During that time he has served as patrol sergeant for 
the Moorpark division and last year was put in charge of the three detectives 
working in Moorpark. 
</P>
<P>
 He said he was looking forward to taking charge of the Moorpark division on 
Monday, but as yet was not planning any new initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
 "It already is a well-run department," Rouse said. "I would like to sit back a 
little and see how it's working before I try and change anything. I don't want 
to change just for the sake of changing."  
</P>
<P>
 Rouse had high praise for his former commanding officer -- the two attended 
the police academy together -- saying Dean was an innovative commander who 
worked well with the community and the deputies under him. 
</P>
<P>
 "(Dean) has a lot to be proud of here," Rouse said. "He accomplished a 
tremendous amount. He's been an effective leader and a personal friend to a lot 
of the deputies here, which not many commanders can do. I think the team spirit 
he developed here has made Moorpark a popular place (for deputies) to work." 
</P>
<P>
 Rouse said one of his most important tasks will be to continue the good 
working relationship Dean established with the Moorpark City Council.  
</P>
<P>
 The city contracts with the Sheriff's Department, which staffs the 20-member 
Moorpark enforcement team. Rouse said the city has made law and order a top 
priority, allocating more than 60% of the city's operating budget to law 
enforcement. The city is now considering increasing the amount spent on law 
enforcement to more than 70% of the budget, or $2.6 million, to maintain the 
existing level of services next year. 
</P>
<P>
 Council members and City Manager Steve Kueny, who interviewed Rouse for the 
job, approved of the new appointment. 
</P>
<P>
 "He's an excellent choice," said Mayor Paul Lawrason. "He's sat in for Dean at 
several City Council meetings, and while he served as patrol sergeant he was 
the person I spoke with if I had any questions about any incidents that 
occurred in the city. He's a very bright professional. I'm really pleased." 
</P>
<P>
 Rouse, who grew up in Santa Monica, said he loves Moorpark, where he has lived 
for nine years with his wife and two children. He said he planned to continue 
his community involvement, which includes volunteering for Moorpark's annual 
Country Days celebration and for his local church.  
</P>
<P>
 "Part of what made (Dean) successful were the relationships he developed in 
the community," Rouse said. "I'd like to see that continue. We want people to 
know that we have an open-door policy. Working out in the community, I feel, is 
the best crime prevention of all." 
</P>
</TEXT>
