<HEADLINE>
<P>
BANKERS SCOLDED OVER THE GAP IN RATES CHARGED AND PAID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Bankers were raked across the coals Thursday, accused by consumers and a House 
lawmaker of jacking up loan rates while keeping a lid on interest rates paid to 
depositors since the Federal Reserve Board tightened its grip on credit. 
</P>
<P>
 But a close reading of the statistics suggests the opposite is true, one 
analyst said. 
</P>
<P>
 Rep. Joseph Kennedy (D-Mass.) charged at a hearing of the banking panel he 
chairs that banks -- through their lending rates -- have passed along to 
consumers the full brunt of the four rate increases engineered by the Fed since 
February. 
</P>
<P>
 The Fed has boosted short-term rates 1.25 percentage points in a bid to head 
off inflation, and Kennedy said banks are "giving themselves a generous markup 
in the process." 
</P>
<P>
 "Not only are (consumers) paying more for loans -- they're also receiving less 
on their deposits," Kennedy said. 
</P>
<P>
 But Robert Heady, publisher of Bank Rate Monitor, says rates on certificates 
of deposit -- a popular place for consumers to park money -- have risen faster 
than rates on auto loans, credit card loans and other personal loans. 
</P>
<P>
 "Being from Massachusetts, I don't want to rain on Joe Kennedy's parade. But 
the thesis doesn't compute," he said in a phone interview from his office in 
North Palm Beach, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
 "If anything, the banks have been under pressure to contain personal loan 
rates because of weak loan demand," he said. "When farms can't sell their 
apples, they don't raise prices." 
</P>
<P>
 Heady, whose weekly newsletter tracks bank interest rate trends, said rates on 
one-year CDs are now at 3.85%, up from 3.08% in early February, before the Fed 
engineered its first rate hike. 
</P>
<P>
 That 0.77 percentage point rise exceeds the increase in rates on new car 
loans, which have increased to 8.35% from 7.91% -- a gain of 0.44 percentage 
point. 
</P>
<P>
 Heady said rates on money market accounts have risen less than CD rates 
because banks are under less pressure to increase money market rates to attract 
funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
