<HEADLINE>
<P>
ST. JOSEPH ADDS MISSION TO AID ITS OWN HEALTH; HOSPITALS: OWNER OF FACILITIES 
IN ORANGE AND FULLERTON BUYS SOUTH COUNTY MEDICAL CENTER AS NEXT STEP IN 
REGIONAL EXPANSION. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANNE MICHAUD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In the continuing consolidation of the health-care industry, St. Joseph Health 
System in Orange said Thursday that it has bought Mission Hospital Regional 
Medical Center in Mission Viejo. 
</P>
<P>
 St. Joseph Health System, which already owns St. Joseph Hospital in Orange and 
St. Jude Medical Center in Fullerton, said it will keep the Mission Viejo 
facility's 1,300 employees in the deal, terms of which were not disclosed. The 
fate of senior executives at Mission Hospital was not clear. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're trying to be in a position to develop regionally integrated health care 
delivery in Orange County," said Tom Porath, vice president of corporate 
services for St. Joseph Health System. 
</P>
<P>
 Mission Hospital is the designated trauma center for South County and one of 
only three such centers countywide. 
</P>
<P>
 In an increasingly competitive health-care environment where hospitals in many 
cases are receiving lower reimbursements for patient care, such a deal is a 
survival tactic, said Trish Anderson, director of Medical Pathways Management 
Corp. in Torrance. Her company puts together such agreements for hospitals and 
physician groups. 
</P>
<P>
 "There are a lot of individual hospitals looking for a partner or two or 
three," Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Such agreements, for example, allow a group of hospitals to buy expensive 
equipment that they can share, Anderson said, so that patients at all 
affiliated hospitals have access to the treatment it provides. Hospitals can 
also save money by consolidating their billing, payroll, accounting and managed 
care contracting departments. 
</P>
<P>
 "Hospitals are affiliating so that they will not have to duplicate services 
and duplicate their infrastructure," said Lori Aldrete, a spokeswoman for the 
California Assn. of Hospitals and Health Systems. 
</P>
<P>
 St. Joseph Health System is a nonprofit organization sponsored by the Roman 
Catholic Sisters of St. Joseph of Orange. It also owns a group of hospitals in 
Lubbock, Tex. 
</P>
<P>
 Mission Hospital, which will keep its name, is a 274-bed acute-care facility 
with an associated 53-bed pediatric center, Children's Hospital at Mission. It 
was sold by the privately held Mission Viejo Medical Development Co. 
</P>
</TEXT>
