<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: ORANGE COUNTY BUSINESS; REAL ESTATE; APARTMENT VACANCY RATE RISES TO 
7.2% THIS SPRING FROM 6.8% A YEAR EARLIER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Debora Vrana, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The apartment vacancy rate for Orange County was 7.2% this spring, according 
to the semiannual survey of the Apartment Assn. of Orange County.That was up 
slightly from a rate of 6.8% a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
 Mission Viejo had the highest vacancy rate, with 11.4% of the apartments in 
that city standing empty. Anaheim was second-highest, with a 10.6% vacancy 
rate. The lowest rates across the county were in Placentia, with 3.7%; Irvine, 
3.9%; and Rancho Santa Margarita, 4.1%. 
</P>
<P>
 The apartment association, a nonprofit group of rental property owners and 
managers, surveyed 82,500 units, or about 25% of the units in Orange County. 
The results were released this week. The association conducts surveys each 
spring and fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
