<HEADLINE>
<P>
PARENTING; MAKING THE ADJUSTMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARYANN HAMMERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 While most children easily adapt to glasses, eye-care professionals recommend 
that parents take several steps to smooth the transition: 
</P>
<P>
 * Develop a positive outlook yourself.Children will not feel good about 
wearing glasses if parents seem worried or depressed about it. 
</P>
<P>
 * For the cutest and most colorful styles -- and the best fit for the tiniest 
tots -- find an optician who specializes in children. 
</P>
<P>
 * Allow older children to take their time choosing a frame style, and check 
out the selection in several stores if necessary. Adolescents should feel their 
glasses are stylish and flattering. 
</P>
<P>
 * Don't get frustrated or impatient if your child does not adapt to wearing 
glasses right away. Youngsters may need a few days to adjust. MARYANN HAMMERS 
</P>
</TEXT>
