ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: YORBA LINDA; BOOK MAY BE TAKEN OFF 5TH-GRADE LIST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Fifth-grade students at Bryant Ranch Elementary School will finish reading "My 
Brother Sam Is Dead," but they may be the last fifth-grade class in 
Placentia-Yorba Linda Unified School District to do so. 
</P>
<P>
 An ad hoc committee recommended Tuesday that the district restrict the book to 
eighth-grade classrooms starting with the next school year.Teachers at Bryant 
Ranch will be allowed to finish teaching the book because the students have 
nearly completed reading it. 
</P>
<P>
 "It doesn't make sense to pull it now," said Assistant Supt. Sharon McHolland. 
"Some students have already done their writing assignments and there isn't time 
to have them read another book." 
</P>
<P>
 McHolland said the district's curriculum committee will vote on removing the 
book from the approved fifth-grade reading list and placing it on the 
eighth-grade list when it meets in October. If the committee follows the 
recommendation of the ad hoc subcommittee, the novel will be replaced on the 
fifth-grade list by a book dealing with the Revolutionary War, she said. 
DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
