ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: NEWPORT BEACH; CITY TO PUT PAINTING BACK ON DISPLAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City Manager Kevin J. Murphy decided Thursday to rehang an oil painting that 
was removed from a City Hall gallery this week after an employee complained 
that it was offensive. 
</P>
<P>
 The move came after the city's Arts Commission passed a resolution Thursday 
morning in support of displaying the work, which depicts a family in the 1930s 
eating watermelon at the beach. 
</P>
<P>
 City officials said the work represented the artist's recollections of a 
family outing at Seal Beach when she was a young girl. The artist is white. 
Figures in the painting have brownish skin. 
</P>
<P>
 A city employee told officials Wednesday that the painting was stereotypical 
and denigrated black people. Murphy said he knew of no other complaints about 
the work, which was one of 30 selected to appear in a new exhibit at City 
Hall.SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
